pull_request.title: Fix module loading in logging config
pull_request.body:
## Summary

Fix issue where custom logging configuration with simple module paths (like `log_config.LOGGING_CONFIG`) caused triggerer and scheduler to fail during startup.

## Problem

When users set `logging_config_class = log_config.LOGGING_CONFIG` in their `airflow.cfg`, the `load_logging_config()` function would fail because:

1. `logging_class_path.rsplit(".", 1)[0]` produces `"log_config"`
2. `import_string("log_config")` fails because it expects a dot-separated path like `"module.submodule.attribute"`
3. This caused `ImportError` and prevented `REMOTE_TASK_LOG` and `DEFAULT_REMOTE_CONN_ID` from being loaded
4. In some environments, this prevented triggerer and scheduler from starting

## Solution

Replace `import_string()` with `importlib.import_module()` in `load_logging_config()`

## Changes

### Code
- in`airflow-core/src/airflow/logging_config.py`, with`load_logging_config()`

### Test
- in `airflow-core/tests/unit/core/test_logging_config.py`
- **Added**: Parametrized test for different module path structures
- **Added**: Test for graceful fallback when remote logging vars are missing
- **Added**: Helper method to reduce test code duplication

## Related Issues

resolves #54414

issue.title: Modernize the integration
issue.body:
This makes use of all the recent changes in the integration.

Some clarifications here:

1.  CONF_ALBUM_ART_TEMPLATE does nothing.  Users should be using CONF_ENTITY_PICTURE_TEMPLATE
2.  ATTR_ENTITY_ID was deprecated upstream almost 5 years ago.  It also does nothing.

I kept both of them in to avoid breaking configurations.

There may be some unforseen behavior changes because the previous version of this integration had outdated ways of updating states.

This new code heavily relies on the upstream MediaPlayer entity to handle all the heavy lifting.  Because of that, we are using the under the hood attributes to set all properties on the object.  This should provide a better user experience with the entity but it may change behavior.

Some new behavior is inherently added as well:

1.  `this` will work in all scripts.
2. `friendly_name` now accepts templates
3. availability behavior will now be consistent with all other template entities.
4. You can now set the state to `None` and the entity will go `unknown`.

In regards to development benefits;
1.  Optimistic states can be added rather easily.
2. New scripts/templates would be easy to add without heavy changes.

commits.message:
feat: consolidate all infrastructure images into dedicated workflow

Infrastructure Workflow Consolidation:
- Create comprehensive infrastructure-build.yaml for all non-agent images
- Move PostgreSQL+pgvector image with high-dimensional vector support (3072-dim)
- Move rust-builder from separate runner-builld.yaml workflow
- Add runtime base image building with dependency management
- Consolidate PostgreSQL image from external repo into cto repo

Workflow Organization:
- agents-build.yaml: Pure AI agents (Claude, OpenHands, Gemini, etc.)
- infrastructure-build.yaml: Infrastructure (PostgreSQL, rust-builder, runtime)
- Proper separation of concerns and logical grouping
- Different schedules (agents at 6 AM, infrastructure at 7 AM)

New Features:
- Selective image building via workflow_dispatch (build specific images)
- Automatic runner cycling when rust-builder image updates
- Enhanced build summaries and GitHub Actions integration
- Support for both scheduled builds and manual triggers

Deprecation:
- Mark runner-builld.yaml as deprecated with clear migration path
- Direct users to new infrastructure workflow for rust-builder builds
- Maintain backward compatibility with deprecation notices

Benefits:
- Better workflow organization and separation of concerns
- Centralized infrastructure management in single repository
- Cleaner build triggers and dependency management
- Production-ready images with proper versioning and caching

Initial file format for `block-delimiters.list`:

     ```block-delimiters.list
     # Description of format 1
     <begin token for format 1>
     <end token for format 1>

     # Description of format 2
     ```

pull_request.title: Refactor and enhance trading strategy analysis
pull_request.body:
This commit addresses three key areas of improvement:

1.  **Centralized Strategy Configuration:** Default parameters for all trading strategies have been moved from being hardcoded within each strategy's class file to a centralized `config/config.json` file. A new `config_loader.py` module has been introduced to load these defaults, making them easier to manage and modify without changing the source code.

2.  **Advanced Performance Metrics:** The performance metrics have been significantly expanded to include standard financial metrics such as Sharpe ratio, Sortino ratio, max drawdown, and profit factor. These calculations are housed in a new `reports/performance_metrics.py` module and are now calculated for each strategy, providing deeper insights into their performance.

3.  **Complete Test Coverage for Strategies:** Comprehensive test coverage has been added for the `BollingerBands`, `FibonacciRetracement`, `IchimokuCloud`, and `VolumeProfile` strategies. This ensures the reliability and correctness of these core components.

issue.title: Android tests generates 0% coverage
issue.body:
I Added test to have a 100% coverage as an Android instrumentation tests "androidTest" folder.

This is a pretty common way to tests classes in Android, some of them are tested as Unit tests and some of them as Android Instrumented Test, It would be great that:
1- be able to have coverage from Android Tests
2- have a merged report from unit test tests in "test" folder and Android tests, tests in "androidTest" folder.
3- if it's a multi module project, it would be great to have a unified report for both unit Tests and Android tests for all modules.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6610535/144761987-c52311c1-f9bb-4430-8d4f-95444ada923b.png)

Android project in (ignore module01 by now)
https://github.com/gerardoepitacio/KoverTest

running
./gradlew clean app:koverHtmlReport

generates a report in app/build/reports where
![Screen Shot 2021-12-05 at 14 06 59](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6610535/144762152-c3bbefbf-0478-45dd-b70a-d29b14cbb5e8.png)

But all methods in RemoteDataProviderImpl.kt are tested.
![Screen Shot 2021-12-05 at 14 07 32](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6610535/144762163-ccae9d07-dfe4-4b53-a6e4-88858f796180.png)

comment.body: I have the same issue on a backend startup test with one of my Koin modules. All of them are correctly working except this one. I know it's not related to Android, but it's the only case I found of a 100% coverage that is ignored on a file, using Kover.
